INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'cb77c797-48d8-45c4-ad85-dd2e9753e0c6',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$BullMQ — Why Queues Beat Direct Calls for Async Workloads$escape$,
  $escape$When your Express route directly calls sendEmail() or generatePDF(), you've coupled request latency to processing time and tied your API's availability to every downstream dependency. BullMQ breaks that coupling by turning side effects into durable jobs.

With BullMQ, the route adds a job to a Queue and returns immediately — the Worker picks it up independently, in a separate process or even a separate machine. If the email provider is down, the job sits in Redis and retries with exponential backoff via the `attempts` and `backoff` options. Your API stays responsive.

Load leveling is the other win. A viral post might trigger 10,000 notification jobs in seconds. Without a queue, your worker pool drowns. With BullMQ, you set `concurrency` on the Worker and the queue absorbs the spike — jobs are processed at the rate your infrastructure can handle, not the rate users generate them.

BullMQ also gives you `priority`, rate limiting via `limiter`, and job deduplication with custom `jobId` — primitives that turn a naive fire-and-forget pattern into a production-grade async pipeline.$escape$,
  $escape$import { Queue, Worker } from 'bullmq';
import { redisConnection } from './redis';

const emailQueue = new Queue('email', { connection: redisConnection });

// In your route handler — returns instantly
await emailQueue.add('send-welcome', { userId, to: email }, {
  attempts: 5,
  backoff: { type: 'exponential', delay: 2000 },
  jobId: `welcome-${userId}`, // deduplication
});

// In a separate worker process
new Worker('email', async (job) => {
  await sendEmail(job.data.to, 'Welcome!');
}, { connection: redisConnection, concurrency: 10 });$escape$,
