INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '562af401-27b4-49d0-8c87-5bd53c265584',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$BullMQ Dead Letter Queues — Poison Message Handling and Backoff Strategies$escape$,
  $escape$BullMQ doesn't ship a native dead-letter queue — you build one. When a job exhausts all retry attempts it lands in the queue's failed set, inspectable via `queue.getFailed()`. The signal to route it elsewhere is the Worker's `failed` event, checked against `job.attemptsMade >= (job.opts.attempts ?? 1)`.

Before a job gets there, configure retry behaviour per-job via `attempts` and `backoff`. BullMQ supports two built-in backoff strategies: `fixed` (constant delay in ms) and `exponential` (delay doubles each attempt, seeded by `delay` ms). Exponential is the right default for transient failures — downstream unavailability, rate limits, lock contention.

Poison messages are a different problem: jobs that fail regardless of retries due to a bad payload or schema mismatch. Re-adding them to the same queue just burns workers. Route them to a dedicated `orders:dlq` queue on final failure, preserving `job.data` and appending the error string. From there you can inspect, replay selectively, or trigger an alert.

Set `removeOnFail: false` to keep failed jobs in Redis for auditing, or `removeOnFail: { count: 500 }` in production to cap memory growth.$escape$,
  $escape$import { Queue, Worker, Job } from 'bullmq';
import IORedis from 'ioredis';

const connection = new IORedis();
const mainQueue = new Queue('orders', { connection });
const dlq = new Queue('orders:dlq', { connection });

await mainQueue.add('process', payload, {
  attempts: 3,
  backoff: { type: 'exponential', delay: 1000 },
  removeOnFail: false,
});

const worker = new Worker('orders', async (job: Job) => {
  await processOrder(job.data);
}, { connection });

worker.on('failed', async (job, err) => {
  if (job && job.attemptsMade >= (job.opts.attempts ?? 1)) {
    await dlq.add(job.name, { ...job.data, _error: err.message });
  }
});$escape$,
