INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '4b520802-d4eb-4774-ae26-d20af866206d',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$BullMQ + Cache-Aside — Reuse Your Redis Connection to Crush DB Load$escape$,
  $escape$BullMQ workers already depend on Redis — every Queue and Worker you instantiate is backed by an ioredis connection. That means caching costs you nothing extra in infrastructure.

The problem: high-throughput workers often fetch the same DB rows repeatedly. A send-notification worker processing 50k jobs/hour that queries user preferences on every job is hammering Postgres with identical reads. The fix is cache-aside using the same ioredis instance BullMQ already holds.

Pattern: on each job, check Redis for the cache key. On a hit, deserialize and proceed. On a miss, query the DB, serialize, write to Redis with a TTL (`SET key value EX 60`), then proceed. The TTL prevents stale data from accumulating indefinitely.

Pass the same `connection` instance to both your `Worker` constructor and your cache reads/writes. BullMQ spawns separate internal clients per role (blocking client for `BRPOPLPUSH`, non-blocking for everything else), but your shared ioredis instance runs alongside them safely.

For lookup-heavy workers, a 30–60s TTL on stable data like user configs or feature flags can reduce DB load by 90%+ with zero added latency on cache hits.$escape$,
  $escape$import { Worker, Job } from 'bullmq';
import { Redis } from 'ioredis';

const connection = new Redis({ maxRetriesPerRequest: null });

const worker = new Worker('notifications', async (job: Job) => {
  const { userId } = job.data;
  const cacheKey = `user:${userId}:prefs`;

  let raw = await connection.get(cacheKey);
  if (!raw) {
    const prefs = await db.getUserPrefs(userId);
    raw = JSON.stringify(prefs);
    await connection.set(cacheKey, raw, 'EX', 60);
  }

  await sendNotification(job.data, JSON.parse(raw));
}, { connection });$escape$,
