INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'e32bd61d-3612-4ce2-8028-6d224a76143d',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$BullMQ vs Kafka — Partitions, Consumer Groups, and Log Compaction Mapped$escape$,
  $escape$Kafka distributes load via partitions; BullMQ achieves similar isolation through named queues. Spin up a `notifications-high` and `notifications-low` queue instead of partition keys — each gets its own Redis key namespace and independent throughput. For consumer groups, BullMQ Workers compete for jobs on a single queue using Redis' atomic `BRPOPLPUSH` under the hood, so concurrency is configured per-worker instance via `{ concurrency: 5 }`. Run multiple worker processes pointing at the same queue name for horizontal scaling — BullMQ handles the fan-out safely without duplicate processing.

Offset management in Kafka is explicit; BullMQ tracks job state transitions implicitly in Redis sorted sets (`waiting`, `active`, `completed`, `failed`). Use `queue.getJobs(['completed'], 0, 100)` to inspect a window of completed jobs — the closest analog to rewinding a consumer offset.

For log compaction: BullMQ has no key-based deduplication like Kafka, but `removeOnComplete: { count: 1000 }` and `removeOnFail: { age: 86400 }` keep Redis memory bounded. Pair with `queue.obliterate()` for full resets during blue-green deploys.$escape$,
  $escape$import { Queue, Worker } from 'bullmq';
import { redisOptions } from './redis';

const queue = new Queue('notifications-high', { connection: redisOptions });

const worker = new Worker(
  'notifications-high',
  async (job) => {
    await sendNotification(job.data);
  },
  {
    connection: redisOptions,
    concurrency: 5,
    removeOnComplete: { count: 1000 },
    removeOnFail: { age: 86400 },
  }
);$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
