INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '4c33291b-88de-4c5f-918c-c5b025e2b35b',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$BullMQ Backpressure — Stopping Memory Blowout When Consumers Lag$escape$,
  $escape$BullMQ stores jobs in Redis sorted sets and lists. When producers outpace workers, the `waiting` list grows unchecked until Redis hits `maxmemory` and starts evicting keys — or crashes outright. BullMQ has no built-in flow control; you own the backpressure logic.

`queue.getJobCounts('waiting', 'active')` is your pressure gauge. Before each `queue.add()`, check whether the waiting depth exceeds a safe threshold. If it does, back off and retry. This is a simple, producer-side throttle that costs one Redis call per enqueue.

On the worker side, `concurrency` is your primary lever. For I/O-bound jobs, push it to 20–50; for CPU-bound work, cap it at `os.cpus().length`. Higher concurrency drains the waiting list faster but increases in-flight Redis reads.

The silent killer: completed and failed jobs. Without `removeOnComplete` and `removeOnFail` on your Worker, every finished job stays in Redis forever. A queue processing 10k jobs/day accumulates millions of stale entries within weeks. Set count-based retention on every worker, no exceptions.

For event-driven pipelines, listen to `QueueEvents` `'drained'` to resume a paused producer the moment the queue empties, avoiding busy-wait polling.$escape$,
  $escape$import { Queue, Worker } from 'bullmq';

const queue = new Queue('pipeline', { connection });

async function enqueue(data: unknown) {
  const { waiting } = await queue.getJobCounts('waiting');
  if (waiting >= 500) {
    await new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, 200));
    return enqueue(data);
  }
  await queue.add('task', data);
}

new Worker('pipeline', processor, {
  connection, concurrency: 10,
  removeOnComplete: { count: 1000 }, removeOnFail: { count: 5000 },
});$escape$,
