INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'e8890a3c-e1ed-4558-b32c-f671ffa5993d',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$BullMQ — Testing Workers in Isolation Without a Live Redis$escape$,
  $escape$BullMQ's `Worker` accepts a plain async processor function `(job: Job<D, R>) => Promise<R>`. That seam is your test boundary — extract the processor separately from the `Worker` constructor and unit-test it directly, passing a mock `Job` object. For the mock, you only need to shape the fields your processor actually reads: `job.data`, `job.id`, `job.name`, and optionally `job.log()` / `job.updateProgress()` if you assert on side-effects.

For integration tests that need real queue semantics — flow dependencies, repeat options, rate limiters — reach for `ioredis-mock`. Pass it as the `connection` option to both `Queue` and `Worker`. Jobs enqueue and process synchronously-enough for assertions without a live Redis. Call `worker.close()` in `afterEach` to drain the event loop; skipping this causes open handle warnings that mask real failures.

Avoid instantiating `Worker` in pure unit tests — it immediately pings Redis and spawns a polling loop. Keep that boundary clean: processor logic in one file, `Worker` wiring in another.$escape$,
  $escape$import { Job } from 'bullmq';
import { processEmailJob } from './email.processor';

const mockJob = {
  id: '1',
  name: 'send-welcome',
  data: { userId: 'u_123', email: 'dev@example.com' },
  log: jest.fn(),
  updateProgress: jest.fn(),
} as unknown as Job<EmailJobData>;

it('sends email and logs on success', async () => {
  const result = await processEmailJob(mockJob);
  expect(result.status).toBe('sent');
  expect(mockJob.log).toHaveBeenCalledWith(expect.stringContaining('u_123'));
});$escape$,
